1. Write a program to print "Good Morning" and "Welcome" continuously on the screen using Threads.
Code
class GoodMorning extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

            System.out.println("Good Morning");
        }
    }
}

class Welcome extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

            System.out.println("Welcome");
        }
    }
}

class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        GoodMorning g = new GoodMorning();

        Welcome w = new Welcome();

        g.start();
        w.start();
    }
}
Output
Good Morning
Welcome
Good Morning
Welcome
...
2. Add a sleep method in Welcome thread of Question 1 to delay its execution for 200 ms.
Code
class GoodMorning extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

            System.out.println("Good Morning");
        }
    }
}

class Welcome extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {

            try {

                Thread.sleep(200);
            }

            catch(Exception e) {

                System.out.println(e);
            }

            System.out.println("Welcome");
        }
    }
}

class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        GoodMorning g = new GoodMorning();

        Welcome w = new Welcome();

        g.start();
        w.start();
    }
}
Output
Good Morning
Welcome
Good Morning
Welcome
...

(Welcome prints after 200 ms delay)

3. Demonstrate getPriority() and setPriority() methods in Java Threads.
Code
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        System.out.println("Thread Running");
    }
}

class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();

        MyThread t2 = new MyThread();

        t1.setPriority(Thread.MAX_PRIORITY);

        t2.setPriority(Thread.MIN_PRIORITY);

        System.out.println("Priority of t1 = " + t1.getPriority());

        System.out.println("Priority of t2 = " + t2.getPriority());

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}
Output
Priority of t1 = 10
Priority of t2 = 1
Thread Running
Thread Running
4. How do you get the state of a given thread in Java?
Code
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        System.out.println("Thread Running");
    }
}

class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t = new MyThread();

        System.out.println(t.getState());

        t.start();

        System.out.println(t.getState());
    }
}
